	(321,3,'2014-11-06 12:24:54','2014-11-06 09:24:54','<p>I am lucky to be a Restless Development youth advocate on SRHR . On the 13th of September I was offered an opportunity to attend a dialogue unique in a way that it didnt only include youth who are some most times on the losing end of government policies but the elderly as well. That Saturday offered a unique opportunity to see how this dynamic plays out and luckily for me I got a couple of lessons from the day long occasion and here are some of them;</p><p>Promotion items like Branded t-shirts, brochures or flyers seem luxurious to some people ,but are the easiest ways of creating rapport especially in a dialogue where everyone is pushing a different issue.</p><p>You dont want yours to disappear in a sea of obscurity. To top it up, preparation before any sort of chance of meeting policy makers gives you a professional feel in the eyes of those you are advocating to.</p><p>Always acknowledge the efforts of policy makers no matter how small it is. When i was starting out as an advocate i always thought about it as a sort of proxy war of advocates against the existing policy makers since i wouldnt understand how i an outsider/ not involved in policy making can easily see all these loopholes while those in the \'system\' just wouldnt see all this even when the issue in question was pertinent and affecting a huge part of the population for example the youth are nearly half the population. Attending this dialogue i wouldnt help but appreciate how all these elderly vastly experienced despite having sharp disagreements with the government would start all submissions by thanking the government for the work done thus far before giving their take on the best way forward.</p><p>Be charismatic and engaging while making your submissions.This helps to keep your audience lively and alert all through your submissions. Good advocacy should be a good mix of both the storytelling and figures to complete the picture.</p><p>For example the head of Helpage International during her submission described a scenario of an elderly going to buy condoms but fearing to be served by a young girl fit to be his daughter. This forced him to visit a clinic managed by his age-mates who he finds reading the bible so to save face opts to buy painkillers</p><p>The story sounds comical however its these kinds of prejudices that both young and old face which sometimes makes them have unprotected sex. </p><p>New media also know as social media are powerful tools especially if used as a key component of any advocacy campaign since it creates immediate connections across borders, opening new frontiers enabling different people to share their different experiences on the same topic at the same time as the event is ongoing. However it needs constant updating especially concurrently as the event is happening so those interested in that specific topic can easily find it but also so that it can capture the attention of other social media users.</p><p>Semakula Emmanuel<br />Youth Advocate 2014<br />Keep It Real Project</p>','Restless Development At The #IGDUG2014','','publish','open','open','','restless-development-at-the-igdug2014','','','2017-07-06 18:28:38','2017-07-06 15:28:38','',0,'http://localhost/rahu/?p=321',0,'post','',0),
